Create a professional UML Sequence Diagram for an enterprise cloud platform similar to Ciright.

Actors:
- Admin
- Employee
- Customer
- Manager

System Components:
- Web UI (Frontend)
- Authentication Service
- CRM Module (Customer Management)
- Work Module (Task & Workflow Management)
- Contract Module
- Project Module (E-Domains)
- Reporting Module
- Database (MySQL)

Flow:
1. User (Admin/Employee/Customer) logs into the system through Web UI
2. Web UI sends login request to Authentication Service
3. Authentication Service validates credentials from Database
4. Authentication Service returns success/failure response
5. After login, user accesses Dashboard

6. Based on role:
   - Admin manages users, teams, business types, and contracts
   - Employee manages tasks and updates customer data
   - Customer views domain and container data
   - Manager views reports and analytics

7. CRM Module handles customer and contact data and interacts with Database
8. Work Module processes tasks and workflow and stores data in Database
9. Contract Module manages agreements and contract data
10. Domain Module manages domain records (domain name, IP, customer mapping)
11. Reporting Module fetches data from all modules and generates analytics reports

12. Final output is displayed on Web UI

Requirements:
- Use proper UML sequence diagram notation
- Include lifelines for each actor and module
- Show message flow with arrows (request/response)
- Keep diagram clean, professional, and structured





Create a professional Entity-Relationship (ER) Diagram for an enterprise cloud platform similar to Ciright.

Entities (Tables):
1. Employee
   - emp_id (PK)
   - name
   - title
   - status
   - doj

2. Team
   - team_id (PK)
   - team_name

3. Team_Members (Mapping Table)
   - team_member_id (PK)
   - emp_id (FK)
   - team_id (FK)

4. Customer
   - customer_id (PK)
   - name

5. Container
   - container_id (PK)
   - name

6. Customer_Containers
   - customer_container_id (PK)
   - customer_id (FK)
   - container_id (FK)
   - active

7. Business_Type
   - type_id (PK)
   - name

8. Parent_Business_Type
   - parent_business_type_id (PK)
   - business_type (FK)
   - parent_business_type (FK)
   - active

9. Contract_Type_Players
   - default_player_type_id (PK)
   - project_type (FK)
   - business_type (FK)
   - active

10. Domains
   - domain_id (PK)
   - domain
   - suffix
   - sub_domain
   - ip_address
   - customer_id (FK)

11. Audit_Logs
   - audit_id (PK)
   - action
   - created_by
   - created_date
   
12.tbl_tab_master
   - tabName
   -tablabel
   -tblSphere(Fk)
   -tblTabGroups(Fk)

Relationships:
- One Employee can belong to many Teams (Many-to-Many via Team_Members)
- One Customer can have many Containers (Many-to-Many via Customer_Containers)
- One Business Type can have a parent Business Type (Self Relationship)
- One Customer can have multiple Domains (One-to-Many)
- Contract_Type_Players is linked to Business_Type and Project_Type
-tbl_tab_master is linked to tbl_sphere and tbl_tab_groups

Requirements:
- Show only entities not show attributes
- Clearly define primary keys (PK) and foreign keys (FK)
- Show relationships with correct cardinality (1:1, 1:N, M:N)
- Use proper ER diagram notation (rectangles, diamonds, lines)
- Keep diagram clean, structured, and professional
